Midgaard reads Akh'enet as a cautionary case against letting legal process and ritual share vocabulary. Akh'enet's failure — water quotas acquiring funerary annotations, death ledgers acquiring ration penalties — parallels the Violet Compact's corruption, where the registry classified condemned persons as "arcane material." Both systems were designed for categorical separation; both were exploited through shared vocabulary. Reckoning notes: Akh'enet's Nadir Palace (court authority, hydraulic regulation, and funerary cosmology in one machine) is the architectural version of what the Sealed Names Apparatus attempted administratively. The Violet Compact was intended to prevent the same contamination and failed by the same mechanism. Continuity notes that Akh'enet's Reed Ledger Warden tradition — civilian continuity through catastrophe — validates maintaining governance through collapse. Reed Ledger Warden records carry partial validity; post-Collapse Akh'enet documents require enhanced provenance review.

