Akh'enet's founding creed — "What is unrecorded becomes famine" — is an empirical claim testable against its own history. Keeper-era systematic recording (thirst oaths, silt tallies, witness stones paired with route distance and cistern allocation) produced functional governance. Under the Jackal Balance Court, records carrying both civic and metaphysical weight caused category blurring and declining predictability. The Bellwind Collapse's mass ledger loss destroyed the measurement baseline: the city could not assess its own state. Record destruction made resource allocation, claim adjudication, and coordinated response impossible. The current Akh'enet — multiple factions claiming legitimacy from partial records they cannot fully interpret — is the downstream consequence. Each faction's authority claim depends on incomplete documentation of the institutional chains that would validate it. Empirical resolution requires records that no longer exist.
